i know that japanese has 3 alphabets<br>
kanji are the hundreds of pictograms with various meanings, katakana are the sounds used to form foreign words, and hiranga are the basic sounds.<br>
(i think thats how it goes at least)<br>
<br>
now, my question is: how much are each of these different alphabets used? are words written in kanji also displayed in hiranga? what percentage approximately is the use of any given character set?<br>
<br>
the other question i had takes a bit of explaining first..<br>
i recently bought on a whim a cd package called &quot;Instant Immersion Japanese&quot; thinking i might slowly pick up something with it. i am absolutely disgusted with it. it has 3 cds and some translation software. the first cd consists of basic vocabulary. common objects, colors, that kind of stuff. ok thats cool. next 2 cd: straight japanese. wait a minute. i think i missed something. umm.. i know nothing about grammar or any rules of the language! so that is pretty much worthless to me. now getting on to the question finally, are any of the other cd based interactive learning packages any better than this? i picked the cheapest one i could find, and obviously, got what i paid for. is there one thats actually useful that people have actually used and enjoyed? <p><hr>
